Wrote failing specs which highlights missing content-type with rack test driverDon't know if this could have been written any better, guess it can asnthis is my first deep look into Capybara. The problem is found in thenCapybara::Driver::RackTest; it doesn't forward the content type of thenfile being uplloaded to Rack::Test::UploadedFile.new. UploadFile'sninitializer sets the content type to text/plain as a default.nnThis will make for instance Paperclip's attachment validation fail whenntesting with Cucumber and Capybara even though we are uploading a typenwhich should pass.n

Ensure that matchers work correctly after actions, closes #171With browser-based drivers, the has_value?, has_select?, andnhas_checked_field? matchers (and their negative counterparts)ndid not always work correctly. It is not possible to determinenthe dynamic state of inputs purely with XPath, because XPathnhas access only to the value, selected, and checked _attributes_,nand only the corresponding _properties_ change in response tonuser input. This commit replaces the pure XPath implementationnwith one that retrieves all matching inputs and then filters thenresults using driver-specific means that do reflect user input.n

Remove broken tests for server_boot_timeoutWhen they were added in 09d6335, responsive? already only hitn/__identify__, which does not hit the server, but gets special-cased innCapybara's Identify server class (and runs instantly).nnSo it's not clear what constitutes a slow server that might time outnat boot, and thus why server_boot_timeout needs to be configurable. Anserver that is slow to respond to HTTP requests would not trigger thenboot timeout. All we really seem to be waiting for within the timeoutnwindow is for Thin or WEBrick to come up.n

Poll for the server coming up more frequentlyCapybara.timeout sleeps 50ms between polls, and since the server tendsnto boot quickly, this is a reasonable value. By not adding anothern500ms, we shave a few seconds off the test execution time, mostly innspec/server_spec.rb.n

Change selector normalization to check for symbolWith this change, any call to `find`, `all`, etc where the first argument is a Symbol, will assume that that Symbol is the name of the selector. This makes the `match` option on the `id` selector impossible, so `find(:foo)` will no longer find elements by id.nnThis change is in preparation for allowing selectors without locators, as discussed in #783, which we will probably hold off with until Capybara 2.1, because it is too much work.nnThis commit ensures we won't have to break the API to make implementing #783 possible.

For Capybara's own test suite, keep default_wait_time always at 1Until now, we had it set at 0 for all tests that did't require `:js`.nBut that would cause flickering failures when tests that didn't requiren`:js` ran against Selenium, e.g. like this:nnvisit '/foo' # asynchronous in Seleniumnpage.should have_content 'Foo' # can fail if visit didn't finish in timennThis change doubles(!) test suite run time, presumably because we arentesting for expected failures in a lot of places, causing us to retrynfor the full default_wait_time period. At this point though I'm not surenif there's a simple way to avoid the performance hit.n

Server#responsive? now rescues all SystemCallError exceptionsIt previously only rescued Errno::ECONNREFUSED and Errno::EBADF. Since the Net::HTTP calls are the only thingnin this method that should be making any kind of system calls, a rescuenof all SystemCallError exceptions (the superclass of all of the Errnonexceptions) will catch these as well as any other system call errorsntriggered by Net::HTTP.n

Fix access to specializations when Selenium::Driver is subclassedThe specializations are stored in a class instance variable. However,nthey are accessed from the specialize_driver method via `self.class`.nnPreviously if this method was called on an instance of a subclass ofnSelenium::Driver, then it accessed the class instance variablenassociated with the subclass (which is nil by default) and not the classninstance variable associated with the Selenium::Driver class as intendednresulting in an exception like this:nn NoMethodError:n   private method `select' called for nil:NilClassn   ./lib/capybara/selenium/driver.rb:417:in `specialize_driver'n   ./lib/capybara/selenium/driver.rb:49:in `browser'n   ./lib/capybara/selenium/driver.rb:66:in `visit'n   ./lib/capybara/session.rb:277:in `visit'n   ./spec/selenium_spec_chrome.rb:118:in `block (3 levels) in <top (required)>'nnThis commit adds a spec using a subclass of Selenium::Driver with Chromento demonstrate the problem and fixes it by changing thenspecialize_driver method to access the specializations via thenexplicitly specified class name.nnAn alternative fix would be to use a class variable for specializationsnand do away with the class attribute reader altogether.n
